"span": {"begin": 1394, "end": 1395}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9900036454200745, "span": {"begin": 1399, "end": 1408}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9551607966423035, "span": {"begin": 1435, "end": 1444}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "17&beta;-estradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994738698005676, "span": {"begin": 1483, "end": 1501}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004970"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.980554461479187, "span": {"begin": 1518, "end": 1525}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.5415830612182617, "span": {"begin": 1559, "end": 1568}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8858050107955933, "span": {"begin": 1613, "end": 1622}}, {"id": ["mesh:C056516"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "exemestane", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9685615301132202, "span": {"begin": 1656, "end": 1666}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000077289"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "letrozole", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9950035214424133, "span": {"begin": 1689, "end": 1698}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000077384"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "anastrozole", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9957991242408752, "span": {"begin": 1703, "end": 1714}}, {"id": ["mim:114480", "mesh:D001943"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "hormone dependent breast cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999890923500061, "span": {"begin": 1740, "end": 1771}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9817782640457153, "span": {"begin": 1856, "end": 1865}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991263747215271, "span": {"begin": 1897, "end": 1905}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9985892176628113, "span": {"begin": 1918, "end": 1926}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999464213848114, "span": {"begin": 1977, "end": 1985}}], "text": "Inhibition of cytochrome P450 aromatase (CYP19; specifically cyp19a1a in fish).&nbsp;  While many vertebrates have a single isoform of aromatase, fish are known to have two isoforms. CYP19a1a is predominantly expressed in ovary while cyp19a1b is predominantly expressed in brain (Callard et al. 2001; Cheshenko et al. 2008). For the purposes of this MIE, when applied to fish, the assumed effect is on cyp19a1a. However, given that both isoforms show similar sensitivity to&nbsp;  aromatase inhibitors (Hinfray et al. 2006) and catalyze the same reaction, discrimination of specific isoforms is not viewed as critical in relative to determining downstream key events resulting from aromatase inhibition in ovarian granulosa cells.&nbsp;  Human aromatase is expressed in ovary, testis, brain, adipose tissue, placenta, blood vessels and bone (Simpson, 2004; Bulun, 2005; Blakemore, 2016; Wang, 2019; Ghosh, 2023).&nbsp;  Responses at the macromolecular level: Aromatase catalyzes three sequential oxidation steps (i.e., KEGG reactions R02501, R04761, R03087 or R01840, R04759, R02351; http://www.genome.jp/kegg/pathway.html) involved in the conversion of C-19 androgens (e.g., testosterone, androstenedione) to C-18 estrogens (e.g., 17&beta;-estradiol, estrone). Aromatase inhibitors interfere with one or more of these reactions, leading to reduced efficiency in converting C-19 androgens into C-18 estrogens. Therefore, inhibition of aromatase activity results in decreased rate of 17&beta;-estradiol (and presumably estrone) production by the ovary.&nbsp;  Aromatase inhibitors can inhibit the enzyme activity. Aromatase inhibitors such as the steroidal exemestane and the non-steroidal letrozole and anastrozole are used in treatment of hormone dependent breast cancer (Wang, 2019; Shoombuatong, 2018; Ghosh, 2023).&nbsp;  Reduced activity or levels of aromatase resulting in reduced levels of estrogen will affect estrogen dependent functions such as reproduction but also estrogen effects in bone, cardiovascular system and central nervous system (Bulun, 2005; Blakemore, 2016).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:18:17 +0000 2026"}